(3386, 1, '2023-10-08 07:53:50', '2023-10-08 07:53:50', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Alex Thiln regularly supervises millions in ad spend every holiday for Opascope clients. And hes learned a thing or two about optimizing ad accounts for end-of-year performance.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He sat down with Opascope co-founder Max Thiln to discuss holiday campaign management best practices.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Watch the full video or read the highlights below.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em><strong>Related: </strong><a href=\"/insights/how-opascope-helped-a-custom-gift-company-increase-holiday-revenue-by-45/\">Learn how we helped increase a custom gift companys holiday ad spend by nearly 45%.</a></em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:embed {\"url\":\"https://youtu.be/TKqTRHo-_jY\",\"type\":\"video\",\"providerNameSlug\":\"youtube\",\"responsive\":true,\"className\":\"wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-youtube wp-block-embed-youtube wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"><div class=\"wp-block-embed__wrapper\">\nhttps://youtu.be/TKqTRHo-_jY\n</div></figure>\n<!-- /wp:embed -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"className\":\"journal-new-page-h3-heading\"} -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading journal-new-page-h3-heading\">1. Set Performance Rules Early</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>During the holidays, things move fast. Your predictions on ad engagement may be way off. Meanwhile, key decision-makers may not be available to approve changes quickly opening the door for missed opportunities as game-time decisions hang in limbo. The result is missed opportunities to maximize revenue.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Some rules to set:&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>1. Whats the minimum and maximum budget youre willing to spend?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>2. What are your scaling rules if ROAS hits certain levels?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For example, if your typical ROAS is 5, but its steadily at 8 during Black Friday week, wouldnt you want to spend as much as possible on ads to take advantage? If the answer is yes, make sure whoever is managing your ads over the holiday have clear guidance on how to deal with a few major if/thens.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Having clear rules set avoids losing time to approvals when things are working and allows maximum value to be captured.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"className\":\"journal-new-page-h3-heading\"} -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading journal-new-page-h3-heading\">2. Dont Test Ads Too Early</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A mistake Alex sees a lot is companies testing out ads well in advance of the holidays.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When it comes to consumer ads, you want to think like your consumers. In this case, that means testing ads when theyre starting to think about the holidays.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you test ads too early, you run the risk of distorting your learnings, because the people engaging with holiday ads in August arent necessarily the same people who would engage in November.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So whats a better approach? Make projections based on last years performance and reuse your best-performing ads. There\'s always value in reusing assets if you can, especially on social, Alex explained, because they have lots of engagement and social proof that\'s going to make them perform better.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"journal-new-page-p-text\"} -->\n<p class=\"journal-new-page-p-text\">Things to keep track of from previous years that can help you optimize the current years performance:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>1. When did Black Friday sales actually start?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>2. Was there a boost early or late?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. What creatives worked the best?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"className\":\"journal-new-page-h3-heading\"} -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading journal-new-page-h3-heading\">3. Test Your Entire Mobile Funnel</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What we\'ll see with most consumer brands is no matter what their normal Facebook/Google split is, traffic is going to usually go more towards Facebook during the holidays just because of the nature of what Black Friday is, Alex explained. As their split leans more toward Meta, brands are going to get more mobile traffic. So if they have mobile issues on site, it\'s going to be much more present during that period and throw off the performance.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Test and retest your funnel using different starting points and, ideally, using different devices. If Android users are getting a different experience than iPhone users and you dont know it, youll miss out.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"className\":\"journal-new-page-h3-heading\"} -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading journal-new-page-h3-heading\">4. Make Small Frequent Changes to Avoid Metas Learning Penalty</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When it comes to managing holiday campaigns, ad managers fear <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/business/help/112167992830700?id=561906377587030\">Metas learning phase</a> (and if they dont, they should.) This is a period of time when Meta is learning the best ways to deliver your ads, and you can expect higher costs and lower engagement.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Learning phases happen when you first submit a new ad set, but you can also trigger a new learning phase when you make big changes to an existing campaign.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Heres what we recommend instead.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>1. Make small increases frequently</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If youre running a Black Friday campaign, dont let ads run all day Friday then make big adjustments to your budgets on Saturday. Not only do you run the risk of triggering a learning penalty, but youre also missing out on opportunities to optimize ROAS. You should be adjusting individual ad budgets up or down all weekend to ensure your budget is going to the best-performing ads.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>2. Duplicate winning campaigns instead of making big budget changes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you have an ad set or campaign performing really well, duplicate it. Increase the budget for the original campaign by 10 or 15% and run the second campaign for a lower amount. In this way, Meta wont penalize you for making a big change and you have a backup ad starting to run just in case.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"className\":\"journal-new-page-h3-heading\"} -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading journal-new-page-h3-heading\">Need Help Managing Your Holiday Campaigns? Talk to Us.</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We work with high-growth companies across a range of industries that have unique challenges and a desire for a true performance marketing partner. If youre ready to boost revenue this holiday (and beyond), <a href=\"https://opascope.com/book-intro-call/\">set up a call.</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'How to Optimize Holiday ROAS', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'how-to-optimize-holiday-roas', '', '', '2024-03-13 08:46:26', '2024-03-13 08:46:26', '', 0, 'http://localhost/opascope-website/?post_type=insight&#038;p=3386', 0, 'insight', '', 0),
(3387, 1, '2023-09-01 07:54:40', '2023-09-01 07:54:40', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When we start working with a new client, one of the first things we do is look to see how their landing pages are implemented. If theyre using a low-code platform like Webflow or Unbounce, we often move them to custom-coded landing pages. We usually use a more optimized framework, typically Next.js.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here are recent results weve gotten migrating two clients landing pages away from low-code platforms.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1. A consumer brand spending 1mm+/month on paid advertising&nbsp;we&nbsp;moved from Webflow to Next.js:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>224% increase in top-of-funnel conversion rates</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>28% increase in mid-funnel conversion rates</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>24% increase in SQL conversion rates</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2. A cloud services provider spending 500k/month on paid advertising we moved from Unbounce to performant WordPress:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>30% increase in conversions&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>22% increase in paying customers</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Why do we see these results? A lot of it comes down to speed.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Low- or no-code builders are designed to make it quick and easy to pull together attractive landing pages or websites, but the same things that make it easy to move elements around ultimately make the code less efficient. This can have a negative effect on page speed which, in turn, impacts conversions.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Moving to custom-built landing pages using something like Next.js will typically accelerate page load by around 30%.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In turn, weve observed that going from slow to fast (sub 30 lighthouse score to 90+ lighthouse score) can lead to anywhere from a 10%-50%+ increase in conversion rates. The average in our experience is around 20%.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That gives us a simple rule of thumb: <strong>If the dev costs associated with improving page speed are less than 20% of what you have spent on ads in the last 3 months, you should do it and it will almost certainly be a net positive.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So do we always recommend steering clear of low-code platforms? Not necessarily.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In this piece, we look at when a platform like Webflow is a good idea and when its time to consider something more advanced.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em><strong>Note: </strong>Want to know how your landing pages are performing? <a href=\"https://opascope.com/book-intro-call/\">Sign up for a performance audit</a>.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:embed {\"url\":\"https://youtu.be/8q6oMLJGb38\",\"type\":\"video\",\"providerNameSlug\":\"youtube\",\"responsive\":true,\"className\":\"wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-youtube wp-block-embed-youtube wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"><div class=\"wp-block-embed__wrapper\">\nhttps://youtu.be/8q6oMLJGb38\n</div></figure>\n<!-- /wp:embed -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Low-Code Platforms Can Work Well For Smaller Marketing Budgets and Moderate Traffic</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Low-code platforms have their advantages. Theyre cheap, fast to set up and have built-in testing functionality.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you have a small marketing budget, say $5K a month or less, then sticking with a cheap and fast landing page builder is in your best interest. At this point, trying to iterate and build out landing pages using developer-heavy resources is probably unrealistic and wont have a high return on investment.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Custom Coded Landing Pages Are Better For Larger Budgets and Heavy Traffic</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As we mentioned above, low-code landing pages are typically slower than the alternative. This can mean a lot when youre sending thousands of users to your landing pages a month.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For companies with bigger campaign budgets, small differences in performance can really add up. For instance, if youre spending $500k a month on paid campaigns that are driving traffic to landing pages, and youre seeing a 5 percent drop-off in users because of the page loading speed, that 5% amounts to $50k per month in wasted spend. 600k per year! Not to mention the loss of revenue that 5% mightve brought in.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At these levels, performance gains may be substantial enough to justify dedicated marketing engineers.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Low-Code Platforms: Ok When Early Stage And Iterating Quickly</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If youre early stage with a business or product, and you\'re moving really fast and making daily changes to your landing pages and testing everything, then it can make sense to use a drag and drop editor that only takes an hour or two to set up and a few seconds to change.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Custom Coded Landing Pages: Better When Ramping Up Spend And Testing in A/B Platforms</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once youve gotten to the point where you may only make a change every couple of weeks or months, your priorities are different. Design speed matters less than optimizing performance.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">The Cost of Development Should Decrease Over Time</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The cost of developing landing pages can vary widely, but once youve got the first landing page built out, you should be able to start reusing components which makes other landing pages faster to develop. You can also build out a CMS which makes deploying landing pages much faster, as well.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Weve also found that marketing teams who have access to their own development resources are able to move faster, test more, and improve the value of their initiatives and assets. Building out performance-optimized landing pages is just one piece of the funnel. (This is why, unlike many other agencies, we have a dev team on staff.)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When teams have to rely on their engineering department (who often have their own priorities) to set up tests, make changes to the funnel, etc, then performance can really suffer.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em><strong>Note: </strong>Landing page optimization is just the start. We work with companies to optimize the entire sales funnel. Sign up for a <a href=\"https://opascope.com/book-intro-call/\">free comprehensive performance audit</a> for personalized recommendations.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Why Low-Code Landing Pages Hurt Conversions', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'why-low-code-landing-pages-hurt-conversions', '', '', '2024-03-13 08:46:07', '2024-03-13 08:46:07', '', 0, 'http://localhost/opascope-website/?post_type=insight&#038;p=3387', 0, 'insight', '', 0),
(3388, 1, '2023-09-01 07:55:09', '2023-09-01 07:55:09', '<!-- wp:embed {\"url\":\"https://youtu.be/mGc8wT-3GPA\",\"type\":\"video\",\"providerNameSlug\":\"youtube\",\"responsive\":true,\"className\":\"wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-youtube wp-block-embed-youtube wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"><div class=\"wp-block-embed__wrapper\">\nhttps://youtu.be/mGc8wT-3GPA\n</div></figure>\n<!-- /wp:embed -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Ive found that the results many CRO or digital marketing agencies present to their clients are fluff metrics.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Theyll run A/B tests on a clients landing page or home page that result in 5-15% increases in engagement or conversions. And everyone is excited.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Over and over again, theyll show successful test results showing 2%, 5%, maybe 10% boosts in performance. And youd naturally assume if you ran enough of these tests with terrific results, that your conversion rates should be doubling or more. And obviously, there should be a significant impact on revenue, right?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Then why is it that all too often, these changes barely impact revenue?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In this piece, Ill cover three big reasons why your CRO efforts might not be directly impacting revenue and what to do instead.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"className\":\"journal-new-page-h3-heading\"} -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading journal-new-page-h3-heading\">1. The Things Youre Testing Are Too Superficial</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One of the most common CRO mistakes I see is companies focusing on the small stuff. Things like adding an extra call to action on landing page, testing different button colors, moving buttons from one side of the screen to the other, etc.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In my experience, these tests focus on superficial changes that dont reflect where prospects are really dropping off.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Common drop-off points include things like putting in payment info or scheduling a call. And if you manage a 5% increase in completing these tasks, youre <em>much </em>more likely to see a similar jump in prospects successfully moving through the entire sales funnel.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The most important question to ask when considering what tests are worthwhile: other than the landing page, where in the funnel are you seeing the highest drop-off?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I recommend starting there.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One important exception: if youre running an ecommerce store with a relatively simple checkout experience and high volume sales, then small changes can add up fast, no matter how superficial.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:group {\"style\":{\"spacing\":{\"margin\":{\"bottom\":\"32px\"}},\"color\":{\"background\":\"#11151c\"}},\"className\":\"journal-new-page-bg-black-texts\",\"layout\":{\"type\":\"constrained\"}} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group journal-new-page-bg-black-texts has-background\" style=\"background-color:#11151c;margin-bottom:32px\"><!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3,\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"fontSize\":\"24px\",\"fontStyle\":\"normal\",\"fontWeight\":\"700\"},\"spacing\":{\"margin\":{\"bottom\":\"30px\"},\"padding\":{\"bottom\":\"16px\"}}},\"textColor\":\"ast-global-color-5\",\"className\":\"takeways-heading\"} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading takeways-heading has-ast-global-color-5-color has-text-color\" style=\"margin-bottom:30px;padding-bottom:16px;font-size:24px;font-style:normal;font-weight:700\">Takeaway</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Locate your most common drop-off posts (where prospects are exiting the funnel) and prioritize your optimization efforts there.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"textColor\":\"ast-global-color-5\"} -->\n<ul class=\"has-ast-global-color-5-color has-text-color\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"className\":\"journal-new-page-h3-heading\"} -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading journal-new-page-h3-heading\">2. Youre Only Testing the Top-of-the-Funnel</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>CRO experts often forget that there\'s a whole funnel to convert.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Its easy to stick with running A/B tests on things that bring new leads into the funnel, but this isnt where youll see the highest value.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The further down the funnel you go, the more prospects youll be able to impact that have the highest purchase intent.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":4291,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\",\"className\":\"single-journal\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image aligncenter size-large single-journal\"><img src=\"https://opascope.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/cro-importing-1024x504.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-4291\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:spacer {\"height\":\"20px\"} -->\n<div style=\"height:20px\" aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:spacer -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you run tests on a landing page, youll only impact leads that come into the site via that landing page. If you work on optimizing checkout, however, youll be impacting everyone in the funnel.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Im not saying you should ignore landing page tests or any other CRO effects at the top of the funnel. But, in general, the lower down the funnel you are, the higher the value. Many businesses make the mistake of only focusing on landing pages and the top of the funnel.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:group {\"style\":{\"spacing\":{\"margin\":{\"bottom\":\"32px\"}},\"color\":{\"background\":\"#11151c\"}},\"className\":\"journal-new-page-bg-black-texts\",\"layout\":{\"type\":\"constrained\"}} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group journal-new-page-bg-black-texts has-background\" style=\"background-color:#11151c;margin-bottom:32px\"><!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3,\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"fontSize\":\"24px\",\"fontStyle\":\"normal\",\"fontWeight\":\"700\"},\"spacing\":{\"margin\":{\"bottom\":\"30px\"},\"padding\":{\"bottom\":\"16px\"}}},\"textColor\":\"ast-global-color-5\",\"className\":\"takeways-heading\"} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading takeways-heading has-ast-global-color-5-color has-text-color\" style=\"margin-bottom:30px;padding-bottom:16px;font-size:24px;font-style:normal;font-weight:700\">Takeaway</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Tests lower in the funnel will have a greater impact on your revenue.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"textColor\":\"ast-global-color-5\"} -->\n<ul class=\"has-ast-global-color-5-color has-text-color\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"className\":\"journal-new-page-h3-heading\"} -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading journal-new-page-h3-heading\">3. Something Is Broken In Your Sales Funnel</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When was the last time you walked through your sales funnel?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When we run audits for prospective clients, were never surprised to find something is broken in their lead or checkout flow. This is especially true since we tend to work with companies with complex sales funnels.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Weve discovered issues like login issues for returning customers  things youd be shocked slip through the cracks. But they do, all the time, at big companies, small companies &nbsp;all across the board.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I try to go through our clients sales funnels at least a couple of times a week to look for issues, as well as things to optimize. If you walk through it often enough on different devices, using different starting points, etc, youll find places of possible friction, new opportunities for upsells or nurturing, and more.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:group {\"style\":{\"spacing\":{\"margin\":{\"bottom\":\"32px\"}},\"color\":{\"background\":\"#11151c\"}},\"className\":\"journal-new-page-bg-black-texts\",\"layout\":{\"type\":\"constrained\"}} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group journal-new-page-bg-black-texts has-background\" style=\"background-color:#11151c;margin-bottom:32px\"><!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3,\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"fontSize\":\"24px\",\"fontStyle\":\"normal\",\"fontWeight\":\"700\"},\"spacing\":{\"margin\":{\"bottom\":\"30px\"},\"padding\":{\"bottom\":\"16px\"}}},\"textColor\":\"ast-global-color-5\",\"className\":\"takeways-heading\"} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading takeways-heading has-ast-global-color-5-color has-text-color\" style=\"margin-bottom:30px;padding-bottom:16px;font-size:24px;font-style:normal;font-weight:700\">Takeaway</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Run through your sales funnel frequently. No tests are going to work well if something is broken.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"textColor\":\"ast-global-color-5\"} -->\n<ul class=\"has-ast-global-color-5-color has-text-color\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"className\":\"journal-new-page-h3-heading\"} -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading journal-new-page-h3-heading\">Want to Know If Your CRO Is Working? Trace It Down the Funnel</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The key takeaway here is to follow the changes or tests you make all the way down the funnel. I try to trace changes directly to either an increase in revenue or a decrease in customer acquisition costs (CAC).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Two examples:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item {\"className\":\"list-white\"} -->\n<li class=\"list-white\">Optimizing a custom gift companys mobile experience played a significant role in a 4% increase in conversion rates and 30% increase in average order value <strong>which led to</strong> an 8% increase in holiday season revenue.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item {\"className\":\"list-white\"} -->\n<li class=\"list-white\">Optimizing a PLG companys landing pages increased conversion rates from .5% to over 3.5% <strong>which led to</strong> 17K more paid user signups per month.&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Because of this, when Im presenting the result of changes my team made to a clients funnel or tests we ran, Im not showing them vanity metrics. Im showing them exactly how our CRO work at Opascope has helped their business make more money or run more efficiently.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If youre ready to find new growth opportunities throughout your funnel, wed love to chat and see if were a good fit. <a href=\"https://opascope.com/book-intro-call/\">Book an intro call</a> with us today to get started.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Why CRO Isnt Impacting Your Bottom Line', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'why-cro-isnt-impacting-your-bottom-line', '', '', '2024-03-13 08:45:49', '2024-03-13 08:45:49', '', 0, 'http://localhost/opascope-website/?post_type=insight&#038;p=3388', 0, 'insight', '', 0),
(3389, 1, '2023-07-12 07:56:14', '2023-07-12 07:56:14', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When a former colleague of Alex got hired by a unicorn scooter company to help the US-based company break into Europe, they quickly discovered theyd inherited a mess.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Their marketing spend was higher than their anticipated European revenue.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Enter Alex.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At the time, it was just Alex doing freelance work. This was before Opascope became a full-fledged agency.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But Alex was known as an advertising problem solver  a skill set thats at the heart of Opascope today. So the manager brought in Alex to run a deep audit of all of the advertising operations across the globe. It took weeks and the result was a hundred-page document detailing his findings and recommendations.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After the audit, the company flew Alex out to work on-site in Amsterdam and sort through the issues hed identified.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Between the deep audit and his first week on-site, Alex was able to decrease marketing costs by 79%.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"journal-new-page-p-text\"} -->\n<p class=\"journal-new-page-p-text\">What follows is the story behind the $8.6MM monthly savings and related insights on agency pitfalls to watch out for &nbsp;especially when breaking into new markets. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"className\":\"journal-new-page-h3-heading\"} -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading journal-new-page-h3-heading\">1. If Your Spend Is In the Millions  Every Detail = $$$</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This was 2018 and the company was in a blitzscaling mindset, which was the thing to do at the time. They were throwing money at everything and marketing very aggressively. Were talking $30 to $40 million global spend per month.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But they were going too fast to do anything well.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Take their market entry plan.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The company was spending around $6 to $8 million a month on ads across Europe. If they continued with the campaign the agency had planned, they wouldve spent between $24 and $32+ million over the course of 4 months. A cost that was higher than the companys anticipated European revenue over that time.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Since the scooter companys primary market at the time was the US, they had a US-based marketing agency running their EMEA account, as well. But the European campaigns were less of a priority and only comprised 10-15% of their overall budget.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As a result, the campaign issues simply got overlooked.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:group {\"style\":{\"spacing\":{\"margin\":{\"bottom\":\"32px\"}},\"color\":{\"background\":\"#11151c\"}},\"className\":\"journal-new-page-bg-black-texts\",\"layout\":{\"type\":\"constrained\"}} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group journal-new-page-bg-black-texts has-background\" style=\"background-color:#11151c;margin-bottom:32px\"><!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3,\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"fontSize\":\"24px\",\"fontStyle\":\"normal\",\"fontWeight\":\"700\"},\"spacing\":{\"padding\":{\"bottom\":\"16px\"},\"margin\":{\"bottom\":\"30px\"}}},\"textColor\":\"ast-global-color-5\",\"className\":\"takeways-heading\"} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading takeways-heading has-ast-global-color-5-color has-text-color\" style=\"margin-bottom:30px;padding-bottom:16px;font-size:24px;font-style:normal;font-weight:700\">Takeaway</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"textColor\":\"ast-global-color-5\"} -->\n<ul class=\"has-ast-global-color-5-color has-text-color\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>If your agency partner isnt interested in or asking to talk to different people throughout your organization, its time to reconsider your partnership.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"className\":\"journal-new-page-h3-heading\"} -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading journal-new-page-h3-heading\">2. Does Your Agency Know How to Handle Uncommon Advertising Situations?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When youre breaking into a new market or running global promotions, sometimes your campaigns arent very straightforward.<br><br>For instance, you might need to educate an audience on a new category or a product they dont understand.<br><br>Or sometimes the promotions arent about the product at all  which was the case with the scooter company.<br><br>See, simply advertising the scooter service wasnt a big deal. The company was a brand name and had a built-in consumer marketing funnel. People would lobby their city to bring the company in. Once approved, seemingly overnight, thousands of scooters would appear on the streets. The scooters themselves were built-in advertising.<br><br>People would scan the QR code they found, get the app, and start using them.<br>This was the real reason that the unicorn company was able to grow so fast.<br><br>Most of the marketing spend was finding the necessary gig workers needed to keep the operation going.<br><br>Nowadays, scooters have interchangeable batteries, so one truck can service an entire city. But back then, the technology didn\'t exist. You had to take the scooters to a centralized location, plug them in, and charge them. This required tons of independent contractors around the city who could do this work.<br><br>So to enter a new city, the company had to go from zero gig employees to 100s within two or three weeks.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"journal-new-page-p-text\"} -->\n<p class=\"journal-new-page-p-text\">The campaign was to find these contractors, but they were running into issues.<br>People were finding the forms to apply and submitting their information, but nobody was actually getting hired. Due to several complications, which well get to, the conversion rate on these ads were abysmal, leading to more necessary spend and diminishing return.<br><br>Its possible if the campaigns had been more common product/service promotions, that spend would have been less and things would have gone smoother.<br><br>But not every agency is equipped to handle unusual situations.<br><br>For instance, a normal best practice for ads is to run them during the day and then shut them off at night when performance is usually lower.<br><br>But when youre targeting people who are free to pick up and charge scooters overnight, this best practice doesnt apply.<br><br>When Alex pointed out this issue, they changed the time the promotions were running, and ad performance increased immediately.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:group {\"style\":{\"spacing\":{\"margin\":{\"bottom\":\"32px\"}},\"color\":{\"background\":\"#11151c\"}},\"className\":\"journal-new-page-bg-black-texts\",\"layout\":{\"type\":\"constrained\"}} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group journal-new-page-bg-black-texts has-background\" style=\"background-color:#11151c;margin-bottom:32px\"><!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3,\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"fontSize\":\"24px\",\"fontStyle\":\"normal\",\"fontWeight\":\"700\"},\"spacing\":{\"padding\":{\"bottom\":\"16px\"},\"margin\":{\"bottom\":\"30px\"}}},\"textColor\":\"ast-global-color-5\",\"className\":\"takeways-heading\"} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading takeways-heading has-ast-global-color-5-color has-text-color\" style=\"margin-bottom:30px;padding-bottom:16px;font-size:24px;font-style:normal;font-weight:700\">Takeaway</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"textColor\":\"ast-global-color-5\"} -->\n<ul class=\"has-ast-global-color-5-color has-text-color\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>To get the best possible results, you need an agency willing to question best practices and think outside the box.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"className\":\"journal-new-page-h3-heading\"} -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading journal-new-page-h3-heading\">3. Does Your Agency REALLY Get Global Advertising?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now, this doesnt have to be an issue if your US-based agency understands the intricacies of localized marketing.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The scooter company\'s original agency didn\'t.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By now, most agencies know that when youre running promotions in different countries, you need localized messaging and ads. But they dont always consider how local cultures and customs can make a difference in campaign performance and how you need to run them.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Through the audit and consulting, Alex discovered that the ads werent set up in a thoughtful way to attract the right audiences per location.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For instance, in France &nbsp;one of the biggest markets that the company was targeting, in order to get hired, an individual needed a SIRET identification number, similar to the USs EIN.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"journal-new-page-p-text\"} -->\n<p class=\"journal-new-page-p-text\">So the conversion rate on finding new workers was much lower when people didnt already have a SIRET number. So one of the first changes that Alex made was creating a lookalike audience to target people who already had this license, or went through the process to get once, a change which improved the quality of people seeing and responding to the ads.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:group {\"style\":{\"spacing\":{\"margin\":{\"bottom\":\"32px\"}},\"color\":{\"background\":\"#11151c\"}},\"className\":\"journal-new-page-bg-black-texts\",\"layout\":{\"type\":\"constrained\"}} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group journal-new-page-bg-black-texts has-background\" style=\"background-color:#11151c;margin-bottom:32px\"><!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3,\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"fontSize\":\"24px\",\"fontStyle\":\"normal\",\"fontWeight\":\"700\"},\"spacing\":{\"margin\":{\"bottom\":\"30px\"},\"padding\":{\"bottom\":\"16px\"}}},\"textColor\":\"ast-global-color-5\",\"className\":\"takeways-heading\"} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading takeways-heading has-ast-global-color-5-color has-text-color\" style=\"margin-bottom:30px;padding-bottom:16px;font-size:24px;font-style:normal;font-weight:700\">Takeaway</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"textColor\":\"ast-global-color-5\"} -->\n<ul class=\"has-ast-global-color-5-color has-text-color\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>When running global promotions, your agency needs to be working with your team on the ground or have the local expertise to maximize performance.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"className\":\"journal-new-page-h3-heading\"} -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading journal-new-page-h3-heading\">Are You Working With Ad Managers or Problem Solvers?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:embed {\"url\":\"https://youtu.be/GtZW6Fh6fm0\",\"type\":\"video\",\"providerNameSlug\":\"youtube\",\"responsive\":true,\"className\":\"wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-youtube wp-block-embed-youtube wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"><div class=\"wp-block-embed__wrapper\">\nhttps://youtu.be/GtZW6Fh6fm0\n</div></figure>\n<!-- /wp:embed -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Its experiences like these that led Alex and Max to found Opascope. They believe in offering marketing services custom-tailored to their clients to maximize revenue.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Where most agencies try to fit their clients into their existing package or process, Opascope adjusts its services to best fit its clients needs. Each and every time.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Where most agencies try to fit their clients into their existing package or process, Opascope adjusts its services to best fit its clients needs. Each and every time.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Want to see what Opascope could do for you? <a href=\"https://opascope.com/book-intro-call/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Schedule a free audit.</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'How Alex Decreased Market Entry Spend By $34mm With An Audit and One Week of Consulting', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'how-alex-decreased-market-entry-spend-by-34mm-with-an-audit-and-one-week-of-consulting', '', '', '2024-03-13 08:45:30', '2024-03-13 08:45:30', '', 0, 'http://localhost/opascope-website/?post_type=insight&#038;p=3389', 0, 'insight', '', 0),
